  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [ ] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (dbfd8d9 2023-09-06T12:58:39.679860620Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nforge t\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nI have a function which behavior depends on `block.number`. It could not be called twice for one block. For invariant test, I added a handler with function:\r\n\r\n```\r\nvm.roll(block.number+1);\r\ntestFunction();\r\n```\r\nAnd it reverts! Furthermore, it's impossible to get stacktrace when it happened.\r\n\r\nThen, I add a storage variable to handler contract `blockNum` and change the code into:\r\n\r\n```\r\nvm.roll(++blockNum);\r\ntestFunction();\r\n```\r\nThis code doesn't revert.\r\n\r\nSo, it seems there is race condition or incorrect mutex for block.number which allow to change it during the parrallel execution",
